## 4. Candidate G-4 — Fingerprint-atlas slot structure after M-subtraction

**Status:** Inherits from prior fingerprint-atlas Phases α–δ; uses an existing instrument; mechanism needs articulation.

### Definition

The fingerprint-atlas (prior arc, see [`substrate_fingerprint_atlas_phase_delta/`](../substrate_fingerprint_atlas_phase_delta/)) extracts a vector of slot values per fixture. The candidate is: which slots retain discriminating power after M-subtraction is applied to the per-record residues that feed each slot. Slots that retain power are G-candidates; slots that collapse are M.

### Mechanism (existing infrastructure, mechanism partial)

**(a) Generative phenomenon.** The atlas slots are designed to capture distinguishable substrate signatures (route, family, parameter regime). If some slots survive M-subtraction with their discrimination intact, those slots are picking up content the BACL lattice does not mandate.

**(b) Counterfactual.** Slots that survive would discriminate fixtures even when the magnitude residue is collapsed; slots that don't survive would lose discrimination under M-subtraction (and thus were riding on substrate content all along).

**(c) Calibration control.** Pre-existing canonical SR and perturbed SR fingerprints: byte-identical pre-M-subtraction (atlas distance = 0.0). Post-M-subtraction, the calibration is: do they remain byte-identical? If so, the slots that captured them are M-only.

**(d) Separation from M and C.** Slot-level granularity helps: slots that depend on integer-j patterns are distinct from slots that depend on magnitudes. Phase 1 characterization can sort the atlas's existing slot set by post-M-subtraction discrimination.

### Phase 0 criteria scoring

| Criterion | Status | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| 1. Computable | **pass** | Atlas infrastructure exists. |
| 2. Survives M-subtraction | **per-slot question, untested** | Some slots will fail (magnitude residue slots); some may pass (integer-j or pattern slots). |
| 3. Discriminates | **untested post-M** | Atlas's discrimination is established pre-M-subtraction; post-M is the open question. |
| 4. Named mechanism | **partial** | A per-slot mechanism is needed; the atlas as a whole does not yet have a unified mechanism statement. |

**Ranking:** Fourth. Uses existing infrastructure; characterization is low-cost (slot survey under M-subtraction). May surface unexpected survivors. Mechanism per-slot must be articulated before Phase 3 graduation.

